, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander de Strivelyn was born in 1188, in Cadder, Lanarkshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Peter de Strivelyn of Cambusbarron, was 38 and his mother, Lady Peter de Strivelyn, was 33. He had at least 4 sons with Marie de Stirling - Baroness of Stirling."},"et":{"1188–":"1188–Surnud","1180–1226":"1180–1226","1188–Male":"1188–Surnud","1192–1270":"1192–1270","1194–Male":"1194–Surnud","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1221–1270":"1221–1270","1237–1304":"1237–1304","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1190":"1190","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1150":"1150","1194":"1194","1270":"1270","1192":"1192","1180":"1180","1304":"1304","1237":"1237","1226":"1226","1188":"1188","1221":"1221","1155":"1155","Cadder, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Cadder, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Ochiltree, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ochiltree, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Strathclyde, Scotland":"Strat